71
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:41,770
is number one, appealing.

72
00:03:41,770 --> 00:03:42,960
Appealing.

73
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:46,090
I love the long E sound.

74
00:03:46,090 --> 00:03:51,020
This means attractive or interesting.

75
00:03:51,020 --> 00:03:56,020
An example, his rich vocabulary
made him sound so appealing.

76
00:03:56,900 --> 00:04:00,570
This is a word that my
mother uses quite a lot.

77
00:04:00,570 --> 00:04:04,730
If she sees something delicious
or smells some nice food,

78
00:04:04,730 --> 00:04:07,703
she'll always say, oh,
that looks so appealing.

79
00:04:08,580 --> 00:04:10,060
It appeals to me.

80
00:04:10,060 --> 00:04:11,640
It's appealing.

81
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:14,653
Number two is ineffable.

82
00:04:15,540 --> 00:04:16,790
Ineffable.

83
00:04:16,790 --> 00:04:21,790
This means too great or
beautiful to describe in words.

84
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:24,320
Something so wonderful

85
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:27,530
that you can't express
how wonderful it is.

86
00:04:27,530 --> 00:04:29,160
It's ineffable.

87
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:30,400
An example.

88
00:04:30,400 --> 00:04:32,480
When I heard of their pregnancy,

89
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:35,650
I was filled with ineffable joy.

90
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:39,030
Number three is nefarious.

91
00:04:39,030 --> 00:04:40,550
Nefarious.

92
00:04:40,550 --> 00:04:43,160
I know a lot of learners
of English struggle

93
00:04:43,160 --> 00:04:45,830
with the /eə/ sound.

94
00:04:45,830 --> 00:04:50,300
Now we are always taught
to pronounce it as /e/ /a/,

95
00:04:50,300 --> 00:04:52,300
together, /eə/.

96
00:04:52,300 --> 00:04:55,840
However, lots of my
students find it easier

97
00:04:55,840 --> 00:04:59,505
to think of it as an
extension of an /e/ sound.

98
00:04:59,505 --> 00:05:01,810
/a/ /a/.

99
00:05:01,810 --> 00:05:03,660
Nefarious.

100
00:05:03,660 --> 00:05:07,430
It might not be what you
find in a pronunciation book

101
00:05:07,430 --> 00:05:10,370
but if it helps you,
then that's fine by me.

102
00:05:10,370 --> 00:05:14,900
Now this might be a beautiful
word in my opinion, nefarious,

103
00:05:14,900 --> 00:05:17,680
but it doesn't have a
very beautiful meaning.

104
00:05:17,680 --> 00:05:21,760
It means criminal or extremely bad.

105
00:05:21,760 --> 00:05:25,350
I like this word because
I find it very expressive.

106
00:05:25,350 --> 00:05:26,470
An example.

107
00:05:26,470 --> 00:05:29,080
They hacked into my bank account

108
00:05:29,080 --> 00:05:32,760
and used the funds for nefarious purposes.

109
00:05:32,760 --> 00:05:37,020
Criminal, extremely bad, extremely bad.

110
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:40,280
Number four is ethereal.

111
00:05:40,280 --> 00:05:41,560
Ethereal.

112
00:05:41,560 --> 00:05:45,130
This means extremely light and beautiful;

113
00:05:45,130 --> 00:05:49,393
seeming to belong to another
more spiritual world.

114
00:05:50,720 --> 00:05:52,350
I think the word sounds beautiful

115
00:05:52,350 --> 00:05:54,830
but I think the meaning is amazing.

116
00:05:54,830 --> 00:05:56,040
An example.

117
00:05:56,040 --> 00:06:00,913
At sunrise, the London
skyline almost looks ethereal.

118
00:06:02,270 --> 00:06:04,950
Number five, if you know me well,

119
00:06:04,950 --> 00:06:09,500
then you might understand
why I love this word so much.

120
00:06:09,500 --> 00:06:11,623
It is epiphany.

121
00:06:12,480 --> 00:06:13,663
Epiphany.

122
00:06:15,120 --> 00:06:16,520
Can you guess why I like it?

123
00:06:17,630 --> 00:06:22,630
It means a sudden and surprising
moment of realisation.

124
00:06:22,740 --> 00:06:26,460
I chose to name my pronunciation
course after this word,

125
00:06:26,460 --> 00:06:28,530
Epiphany Language Studios.

126
00:06:28,530 --> 00:06:32,860
This is because I want my
students to have an epiphany,

127
00:06:32,860 --> 00:06:36,330
a moment of realisation and understanding

128
00:06:36,330 --> 00:06:38,020
when it comes to their language skills

129
00:06:38,020 --> 00:06:40,150
and their pronunciation.

130
00:06:40,150 --> 00:06:41,350
An example.

131
00:06:41,350 --> 00:06:43,100
When she took the course,

132
00:06:43,100 --> 00:06:47,770
she had an epiphany and
everything became clear.

133
00:06:47,770 --> 00:06:51,930
Number six, short, but sweet, angst.

134
00:06:51,930 --> 00:06:53,180
Angst.

135
00:06:53,180 --> 00:06:57,290
It's a feeling of great worry or concern

136
00:06:57,290 --> 00:07:00,290
about your situation or your life.

137
00:07:00,290 --> 00:07:03,840
You often hear teenage angst.

138
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:08,840
I wrote emotional poetry when
I was full of teenage angst.

139
00:07:10,180 --> 00:07:13,390
Number seven is euphoria.

140
00:07:13,390 --> 00:07:14,770
Euphoria.

141
00:07:14,770 --> 00:07:19,770
This means an extremely
strong feeling of excitement

142
00:07:19,810 --> 00:07:24,120
or happiness that usually
only lasts a short while.

143
00:07:24,120 --> 00:07:25,460
An example.

144
00:07:25,460 --> 00:07:27,890
After receiving the letter of acceptance,

145
00:07:27,890 --> 00:07:30,613
I was in a state of euphoria.

146
00:07:31,560 --> 00:07:35,120
Number eight is cherish.

147
00:07:35,120 --> 00:07:36,620
Cherish.

148
00:07:36,620 --> 00:07:40,520
This is a verb meaning to
love someone or something

149
00:07:40,520 --> 00:07:44,890
very much and wanting
to protect them or it.

150
00:07:44,890 --> 00:07:46,160
An example.

151
00:07:46,160 --> 00:07:49,000
I will always cherish
the letter he wrote to me

152
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,260
before he moved away.

153
00:07:51,260 --> 00:07:54,209
Number nine is eternity.

154
00:07:54,209 --> 00:07:55,750
Eternity.

155
00:07:55,750 --> 00:07:59,440
This simply means time without end.

156
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:04,440
For example, a mother's
love lasts for eternity.

157
00:08:04,610 --> 00:08:07,920
Number 10 is quintessence.

158
00:08:07,920 --> 00:08:09,660
Quintessence.

159
00:08:09,660 --> 00:08:12,990
You may have heard it's
adjective form before,

160
00:08:12,990 --> 00:08:16,980
quintessential, which
is also very beautiful,

161
00:08:16,980 --> 00:08:20,320
but I think this one
is used less frequently

162
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:23,610
and I simply believe it should
be used more frequently.

163
00:08:23,610 --> 00:08:26,880
It's a very good word, quintessence.

164
00:08:26,880 --> 00:08:30,690
It means the perfect example of something.

165
00:08:30,690 --> 00:08:31,890
An example.

166
00:08:31,890 --> 00:08:35,309
It was the quintessence of
an English country cottage.

167
00:08:35,309 --> 00:08:38,939
If you see a perfect country cottage

168
00:08:38,940 --> 00:08:41,200
with beautiful light
stone and roses up it,

169
00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:43,510
you can say that is the quintessence

170
00:08:43,510 --> 00:08:45,620
of an English country cottage.

171
00:08:45,620 --> 00:08:47,160
English country cottage.

172
00:08:47,160 --> 00:08:48,480
That's a hard thing to say.

173
00:08:48,480 --> 00:08:50,640
Try repeating that three times.

174
00:08:50,640 --> 00:08:54,100
Number 11 is plethora.

175
00:08:54,100 --> 00:08:54,950
Plethora.

176
00:08:54,950 --> 00:08:58,950
This one does roll off
the tongue, plethora.

177
00:08:58,950 --> 00:09:02,340
It means an amount that
is greater than is needed

178
00:09:02,340 --> 00:09:04,030
or can be used.

179
00:09:04,030 --> 00:09:05,100
For example.

180
00:09:05,100 --> 00:09:09,150
The article contained a
plethora of information.

181
00:09:09,150 --> 00:09:14,010
We're implying that there's
slightly too much information,

182
00:09:14,010 --> 00:09:17,550
maybe in a good way,
just so much information

183
00:09:17,550 --> 00:09:21,760
more than I could ever take
in, a plethora of information.

184
00:09:21,760 --> 00:09:24,810
That might be one of my all
time favourites, actually,

185
